1
00:00:01,988 --> 00:00:12,798
This morning I'd like to talk about the Four Noble Truths, which was the way the Buddha explained his understanding the first time he gave a talk after his enlightenment.

2
00:00:14,720 --> 00:00:23,629
So the four truths are, first of all, the truth of dukkha, dukkha being, you could say, unsatisfactoriness, the unsatisfactory nature of life.

3
00:00:24,929 --> 00:00:30,696
The second truth then is the cause of this unsatisfactoriness in our lives.

4
00:00:31,570 --> 00:00:34,154
And the third is the cessation.

5
00:00:35,877 --> 00:00:36,578
It's the good news.

6
00:00:36,637 --> 00:00:43,268
It's the fact that this unhappiness, a sense of that life doesn't satisfy our needs, that that can all cease.

7
00:00:44,951 --> 00:00:49,398
And then the fourth truth is the path leading to that cessation.

8
00:00:52,843 --> 00:00:57,831
So the first truth anyway, dukkha, the truth, it's often called the truth of suffering.

9
00:00:58,503 --> 00:01:04,671
But suffering is really too strong a word because it sounds very, very extreme.

10
00:01:04,710 --> 00:01:14,822
Whereas in the Buddha's understanding, even minor little irritations that we would think we could cope with okay, that would be included in dukkha.

11
00:01:15,644 --> 00:01:19,868
And even happy states would be included.

12
00:01:20,290 --> 00:01:24,375
And the reason for that is because the happiness doesn't last forever.

13
00:01:25,182 --> 00:01:29,146
So he would consider them unsatisfactory as well because they don't last forever.

14
00:01:32,688 --> 00:01:37,254
So a better translation then for dukkha really is unsatisfactoriness.

15
00:01:38,275 --> 00:01:54,209
And Joseph Goldstein just traced out the pali, you know, for the word and found that I think du means bad or badly made and ka is the hole into which an axle fits in a wheel.

16
00:01:54,730 --> 00:01:57,393
So if you can think of that, a badly made axle hole.

17
00:01:57,873 --> 00:02:00,057
So basically it ends up in a very bumpy ride.

18
00:02:00,596 --> 00:02:01,438
Bump, bump, bump.

19
00:02:01,457 --> 00:02:05,864
So life is a bumpy ride, basically, is what this first noble truth is saying.

20
00:02:05,903 --> 00:02:14,474
Now, each of the four truths comes with some injunction, you know, some instruction for us.

21
00:02:14,794 --> 00:02:20,502
And the first one is to really understand, really, really understand the truth of Dukkha.

22
00:02:22,759 --> 00:02:48,852
so we're asked to look at our life and see what is unsatisfactory in life is life unsatisfying for us so there's obvious areas of difficulty like pain illness loss of those we love various disappointments we come to in life aging of course death so there's many many aspects of life which are very very obviously

23
00:02:49,372 --> 00:03:19,227
unsatisfying for us but then there's other aspects to life you know there's sunshine there's birdsong there's um friendship there's art you know there's very beautiful aspects to life so in what sense can these also be called unsatisfying now they do make us happy you know um lovely sunshine and birdsong definitely they they cheer us up they give us a great lift it's wonderful

24
00:03:20,117 --> 00:03:22,300
But the question is, can they make us happy forever?

25
00:03:23,543 --> 00:03:25,344
Can we base our life on them?

26
00:03:25,626 --> 00:03:26,948
Can we stake our life on them?

27
00:03:29,211 --> 00:03:40,766
And even, for example, if maybe you're in a very loving relationship, we just pretend, a really loving relationship where you just feel yourself completely cherished within the relationship.

28
00:03:41,026 --> 00:03:45,554
Somebody recognises you for who you are and really feels genuine warmth and love for you.

29
00:03:45,614 --> 00:03:50,039
So that's a very, very beautiful relationship for any of us to experience.

30
00:03:51,302 --> 00:03:58,129
Now, the awful possibility is that ten years later or whatever, the other person can just tire of you and go off with somebody else.

31
00:03:58,270 --> 00:04:00,231
That happens all the time, unfortunately.

32
00:04:01,453 --> 00:04:03,474
So, where does that leave us?

33
00:04:04,355 --> 00:04:18,288
Probably incredibly hurt and angry and let down and shocked and bewildered and life in disarray and really not knowing where to start again or what to do with ourselves.

34
00:04:18,504 --> 00:04:26,495
maybe a lot of shame even as well, a sense of failure, bewilderment, how could this happen, and so on.

35
00:04:26,555 --> 00:04:34,725
So it can lead to huge, huge, huge upset, of course, when whatever we based our happiness on just suddenly disappears for one reason or another.

36
00:04:34,766 --> 00:04:47,701
So that's the sense in which even the most beautiful aspects of life can't be totally relied upon, that they fade away.

37
00:04:48,255 --> 00:04:53,961
You know, if the other person doesn't go away out of unfaithfulness, eventually they might get sick and die.

38
00:04:54,642 --> 00:05:01,790
So again, we're left without that person cherishing us, looking after us, helping us feel worthwhile.

39
00:05:04,012 --> 00:05:07,536
So the whole bereavement process brings us really to the same sort of a place.

40
00:05:10,298 --> 00:05:15,985
So if we base our life on any of the worldly happinesses, such as a loving marriage,

41
00:05:16,555 --> 00:05:32,189
success maybe in our career, a skill we have, all of these do fall apart, will fall apart, either with our old age, they'll either fall apart before our old age and death are at that time.

42
00:05:33,471 --> 00:05:44,622
So everything falls apart in this life, you know, and that's the truth of this aspect of dukkha, anicca dukkha, it's called, anicca meaning transience.

43
00:05:45,817 --> 00:05:47,098
the transience of all life.

44
00:05:47,399 --> 00:05:50,745
And because things are changing, they can't be relied upon for happiness.

45
00:05:53,269 --> 00:06:01,142
So the Buddha himself came to realize this in what was for him, I think, his late 20s.

46
00:06:01,182 --> 00:06:10,017
It would have been thought of as midlife in those days, I understand anyway, that he had had a very, very privileged upbringing.

47
00:06:10,824 --> 00:06:17,932
He was a prince and very much respected and very skilled and very talented, very beloved.

48
00:06:17,992 --> 00:06:24,577
And he really had been protected from the truths of life.

49
00:06:25,338 --> 00:06:32,365
And he became very, very painfully and suddenly aware of the fact that people get sick.

50
00:06:32,985 --> 00:06:37,170
He just recognised that and that it could happen to him.

51
00:06:38,077 --> 00:06:40,000
You know, other people get sick, it could happen to me.

52
00:06:40,620 --> 00:06:46,067
He realised that people age, and just as other people age, he was going to age.

53
00:06:47,310 --> 00:06:49,312
And also, people die.

54
00:06:49,692 --> 00:06:52,495
And just like everyone else was going to die, he was also going to die.

55
00:06:53,557 --> 00:07:03,310
So just in a kind of shocked bewilderment of that, just realising that all his happiness, all his pleasure, all his skill, his...

56
00:07:03,593 --> 00:07:31,473
place in society it was all going to disintegrate with these inevitable comings of sickness old age and death he could no longer invest really in his position he could no longer take any interest in it or um take any happiness out of it you know in that in those terms life just wasn't worth living so the kind of angst and um

57
00:07:31,994 --> 00:07:55,487
The anxiety posed by that caused him to leave his palaces, an incredibly courageous decision, go off and join, there was wandering ascetics in those days, people who would really wander with no money, no home, just living a homeless life, wandering through the woods, through the countryside, living off alms, begging for alms.

58
00:07:56,125 --> 00:07:57,446
and searching for truth.

59
00:07:57,687 --> 00:08:00,529
There was a real spiritual quest going on in those days.

60
00:08:01,269 --> 00:08:03,232
So he just joined the spiritual seekers.

61
00:08:05,153 --> 00:08:09,899
And luckily for us, he found a way to the end of suffering.

62
00:08:12,341 --> 00:08:17,726
Now, it takes, I think, an awful lot of courage for us to be really able to see those three.

63
00:08:17,747 --> 00:08:24,394
They're called devadutas, sickness, old age and death, the messengers of the gods, the reality of this life.

64
00:08:24,997 --> 00:08:29,762
But it takes so much courage for us to actually see that that's coming our way.

65
00:08:30,142 --> 00:08:32,024
We shun it in all kinds of ways.

66
00:08:32,125 --> 00:08:34,245
We shun that truth and avoid it.

67
00:08:35,006 --> 00:08:40,952
But we can learn this truth of anicca transience in less threatening ways, I think.

68
00:08:40,972 --> 00:08:44,635
And certainly that's the way I'm gradually, gradually taking it all in.

69
00:08:45,976 --> 00:08:52,423
So I think my first taste of it, you know, that happiness can't be relied upon forever.

70
00:08:52,927 --> 00:08:57,312
came through the whole experience of what for me was a great happiness was the pleasure of reading.

71
00:08:58,594 --> 00:08:59,916
You know, I would always love books.

72
00:08:59,975 --> 00:09:06,504
I was really an avid reader as a child and I was always, you know, in bookshops and getting new books.

73
00:09:06,764 --> 00:09:10,990
And if I had to wait anywhere, it was just no problem so long as I had a book.

74
00:09:11,009 --> 00:09:13,913
And if I had to meet someone and they were an hour late, it didn't matter so long as I had a book.

75
00:09:13,933 --> 00:09:20,363
So I almost had my own escape from dukkha, you know, that nothing mattered so long as I had a book to read.

76
00:09:21,023 --> 00:09:22,225
I could be happy.

77
00:09:23,234 --> 00:09:33,537
And so it was a really, really, really genuine pleasure for me and really protected me from an awful lot of unhappiness in life.

78
00:09:34,440 --> 00:09:42,136
But then, you know, as I started meditation, it just all began to fall apart.

79
00:09:42,590 --> 00:09:50,317
And really it fell apart with the insight that I was escaping from life, that this was an escape.

80
00:09:50,998 --> 00:09:55,182
This happiness was not genuine.

81
00:09:55,221 --> 00:09:57,964
It was an attempt to escape the realities of life.

82
00:09:59,405 --> 00:10:09,575
So just how it actually materialised was I was just better able to acknowledge the emotions around the ending of each book.

83
00:10:09,695 --> 00:10:11,836
And I saw, I remember one particular book where

84
00:10:12,475 --> 00:10:17,440
I just was so sad when it ended that I kept on making up stories about the characters.

85
00:10:17,500 --> 00:10:19,182
It was like I was trying to compose the next book.

86
00:10:19,582 --> 00:10:20,984
I couldn't let those characters go.

87
00:10:21,004 --> 00:10:34,799
And then I remember a book after that where I was turning the pages somewhere around the middle of the book and I just became horribly aware that the pages on this side were less than the pages on that side.

88
00:10:36,240 --> 00:10:42,447
So that whole truth of transience was manifesting, you could say, in the turn of every page.

89
00:10:42,664 --> 00:10:46,990
Each page turn was just a torture because it was bringing me closer and closer and closer to the end.

90
00:10:48,152 --> 00:10:54,879
And a real anxiety just emerged with that particular book anyway.

91
00:10:55,440 --> 00:11:09,297
And when that book did come to an end, I just had to come to the dread realisation that yes, this attempt of mine to bury myself in the written word was just screening out life.

92
00:11:09,682 --> 00:11:10,803
I was screening out life.

93
00:11:10,964 --> 00:11:12,846
I was not facing up to the reality of life.

94
00:11:14,509 --> 00:11:18,434
So it wasn't an escape from dukkha in any genuine sense.

95
00:11:18,674 --> 00:11:20,376
It was an escape from life.

96
00:11:22,460 --> 00:11:24,302
And it also made me very ashamed.

97
00:11:24,403 --> 00:11:34,037
I just realised that, that I was ashamed at having taken what I could see as a sort of a cowardly way out, not really facing life and just escaping from it.

98
00:11:34,057 --> 00:11:36,120
So there was a lot of shame involved there.

99
00:11:36,179 --> 00:11:37,562
And

100
00:11:38,014 --> 00:11:41,600
In retrospect, it's very strange that I'd never noticed that before.

101
00:11:41,620 --> 00:11:47,607
I had been reading for probably 40 years at that stage, and I had really never noticed the sadness around endings.

102
00:11:49,110 --> 00:11:54,096
And it is amazing how we can gloss over this for ourselves at all kinds of endings.

103
00:11:54,397 --> 00:12:00,183
Even when we're saying goodbye to someone, we're nearly always saying, well, I'll see you, and we're working out when we'll see them again.

104
00:12:00,245 --> 00:12:04,990
So we're, in a sense, not acknowledging the fact that this is a parting.

105
00:12:06,893 --> 00:12:07,413
And...

106
00:12:08,221 --> 00:12:13,086
Yeah, we escape from endings usually by thinking of the next new beginning.

107
00:12:13,547 --> 00:12:19,153
So in my case, it might be that I just would think immediately of a new book or I'd phone a friend or I'd do something.

108
00:12:19,173 --> 00:12:23,136
So we do shield ourselves from the truth of dukkha.

109
00:12:26,620 --> 00:12:31,966
And one very strong way we do it is to brush over endings, to really pretend they're not happening.

110
00:12:33,432 --> 00:12:40,139
So how can it help us to look at life in this sort of very honest way?

111
00:12:41,221 --> 00:12:43,904
Well, like the Buddha, but maybe not quite so dramatic.

112
00:12:44,325 --> 00:12:46,567
It did force me to look deeper into my life.

113
00:12:46,908 --> 00:12:54,216
And what I found was that so much had lost its fascination for me.

114
00:12:54,778 --> 00:12:58,562
So career, for example, even relationships,

115
00:12:58,980 --> 00:13:06,692
I just realised that none of them had lived up to whatever expectations I'd had from them, that I was living under false expectations.

116
00:13:08,034 --> 00:13:14,785
But when I looked at it, the only thing that hadn't disappointed me in this way was meditation practice.

117
00:13:14,806 --> 00:13:24,701
So I could see that this was the one area that I had cultivated in life which still held a promise of a genuine, deep possibility of happiness.

118
00:13:26,470 --> 00:13:42,974
Now, I didn't, like the Buddha, cut off my hair and go wandering in a homeless way, but I did take a three-day week and step down from a lot of responsibilities and took a conscious decision to give up on the endless search for a happy relationship and just put all my effort into the spiritual life.

119
00:13:46,678 --> 00:13:49,062
And it was a great relief to take that decision.

120
00:13:49,121 --> 00:13:54,570
It really was a relief to be able to genuinely say for myself, so much hasn't worked out.

121
00:13:55,546 --> 00:13:57,908
It sounds very sad, but in actual fact it was a relief.

122
00:14:00,169 --> 00:14:03,793
And when I look back on it, it was a real turning point in life for me.

123
00:14:03,833 --> 00:14:05,235
Things started getting better from there.

124
00:14:05,936 --> 00:14:17,105
So that genuine look at life caused by opening to this truth of Anicca Dukkha really did start making my life more genuinely happy.

125
00:14:20,928 --> 00:14:23,831
So I began then with the spiritual journey

126
00:14:24,030 --> 00:14:31,801
and meditation practice to see more deeply into this truth of Anicca and how I've been describing it a little bit before.

127
00:14:32,743 --> 00:14:35,986
At the start of things, there's great hope and promise.

128
00:14:36,548 --> 00:14:42,034
You know, for me, the start is very, very uplifting, very invigorating.

129
00:14:43,076 --> 00:14:46,660
There's a lot of gladness and energy for me around the start of things.

130
00:14:48,364 --> 00:14:50,046
But what does the ending mean?

131
00:14:50,407 --> 00:14:52,669
And this is always just a question for me.

132
00:14:52,730 --> 00:14:53,750
And the ending, the footsteps.

133
00:14:54,270 --> 00:14:55,873
It's just symbolic of it all.

134
00:14:56,715 --> 00:14:57,735
It's like an absence.

135
00:14:58,697 --> 00:15:01,883
It leaves me bewildered, wondering what was all that about?

136
00:15:01,923 --> 00:15:08,932
So basically I saw that I was expecting the world to deliver happiness to me.

137
00:15:09,914 --> 00:15:14,883
Whatever way I had interpreted the cultural messages we get, I was doing my share.

138
00:15:14,903 --> 00:15:16,946
I was putting a lot of energy into life.

139
00:15:16,985 --> 00:15:22,354
I was putting all my resources into things and giving to life in that sense.

140
00:15:22,604 --> 00:15:25,628
But there was the expectation that life should then deliver happiness.

141
00:15:27,210 --> 00:15:30,634
And just the realisation that life wasn't doing its share of the bargain.

142
00:15:31,416 --> 00:15:33,158
I was doing mine, but it wasn't doing its.

143
00:15:37,063 --> 00:15:43,832
So anyway, it just showed me the false promise we have in our culture.

144
00:15:44,013 --> 00:15:45,215
If I work hard, I'll be happy.

145
00:15:46,336 --> 00:15:48,779
It's one that went very, very deep into me.

146
00:15:49,975 --> 00:16:03,057
So really this truth of anicca, transience, is telling us that because everything is slipping away and changing, nothing in this world can actually deliver permanent happiness.

147
00:16:03,197 --> 00:16:04,619
It's beyond its capability.

148
00:16:06,581 --> 00:16:14,294
Career, relationships, everything, they're all changing and slipping away so that we can't rely on them.

149
00:16:16,552 --> 00:16:20,197
But as we were talking about the other day, there is also unworldly happiness.

150
00:16:21,039 --> 00:16:27,950
So, for example, meta, you know, genuine friendship, wishing each other well, care for one another, compassion.

151
00:16:29,231 --> 00:16:32,657
So these are sources of genuine happiness for us.

152
00:16:32,917 --> 00:16:35,881
And on this we can rely and we can actually build.

153
00:16:36,863 --> 00:16:38,946
This is a genuine source of happiness for us.

154
00:16:40,148 --> 00:16:42,831
So we can develop all of these qualities.

155
00:16:44,193 --> 00:16:45,395
And we do it here by

156
00:16:45,899 --> 00:16:49,523
attending to each moment without an expectation of return.

157
00:16:50,403 --> 00:16:54,989
We're giving our attention to the breath, the footstep, without any agenda.

158
00:16:56,811 --> 00:16:59,192
So it's a giving without an expectation.

159
00:17:00,955 --> 00:17:14,589
So we're training ourselves to give just really for the sake of giving, which is generosity and which is one of the unworldly happinesses, which we can rely on.

160
00:17:15,211 --> 00:17:17,453
And what we're giving is attention, which is a lot.

161
00:17:17,513 --> 00:17:18,776
I mean, attention is huge.

162
00:17:18,816 --> 00:17:20,278
You know, we all crave attention.

163
00:17:20,298 --> 00:17:21,740
We crave attention from one another.

164
00:17:21,780 --> 00:17:25,365
And most deeply, I think we crave it from ourselves.

165
00:17:26,748 --> 00:17:31,253
So here we're learning to give attention generously.

166
00:17:32,876 --> 00:17:38,444
So we are giving to ourselves in a very, very deep way here.

167
00:17:38,484 --> 00:17:42,130
Our deepest need is for understanding of the world.

168
00:17:42,801 --> 00:17:51,019
And that understanding which is born of immersing ourselves in the actuality of life moment after moment to let the truth seep into us.

169
00:17:52,201 --> 00:17:54,685
So we are giving to ourselves in a very, very deep way.

170
00:17:54,705 --> 00:17:58,093
So...

171
00:18:04,147 --> 00:18:16,169
This is our escape really from the fact that the world doesn't deliver to us, is to give to what we know of the world, sensations, feelings, give our full attention to them.

172
00:18:17,310 --> 00:18:23,642
And in that giving, coming to what we really need to understand, the truth of life.

